---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'SafetyWing in Costa Rica', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-considerations', text: 'Visa Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-types', text: 'Coverage Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pricing', text: 'Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'using-in-costa-rica', text: 'Using SafetyWing in Costa Rica', level: 2 },
  { id: 'caja-relationship', text: 'CAJA and SafetyWing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose SafetyWing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in Costa Rica', href: '/countries/costa-rica/insurance' },
  { title: 'SafetyWing Review', href: '/providers/safetywing' },
  { title: 'SafetyWing vs Cigna', href: '/compare/safetywing-vs-cigna-global' },
];

const coverageColumns = [
  { key: 'benefit', header: 'Benefit' },
  { key: 'nomad', header: 'Nomad Insurance' },
  { key: 'remote', header: 'Remote Health' },
];

const coverageRows = [
  { benefit: 'Type', nomad: 'Travel Medical', remote: 'Health Insurance' },
  { benefit: 'Maximum Coverage', nomad: '$250,000', remote: '$1M-$10M' },
  { benefit: 'Outpatient', nomad: 'Emergency only', remote: 'Full coverage' },
  { benefit: 'Routine Care', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'Covered' },
  { benefit: 'Mental Health', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'Included' },
  { benefit: 'Pre-existing', nomad: 'Not covered', remote: 'After waiting period' },
  { benefit: 'Visa Compliant', nomad: 'Unlikely', remote: 'Possibly' },
  { benefit: 'Commitment', nomad: 'None', remote: 'Monthly' },
];

const pricingColumns = [
  { key: 'age', header: 'Age' },
  { key: 'nomad', header: 'Nomad Insurance' },
  { key: 'remote', header: 'Remote Health' },
];

const pricingRows = [
  { age: '25-39', nomad: '$45/4 weeks (~$49/mo)', remote: '$100-200/mo' },
  { age: '40-49', nomad: '$76/4 weeks (~$83/mo)', remote: '$150-300/mo' },
  { age: '50-59', nomad: '$117/4 weeks (~$127/mo)', remote: '$250-450/mo' },
  { age: '60-69', nomad: '$189/4 weeks (~$205/mo)', remote: '$400-700/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="SafetyWing Insurance in Costa Rica"
  description="Guide to using SafetyWing in Costa Rica. Affordable nomad coverage with important visa and CAJA considerations. Coverage details and who it's right for."
  headline="SafetyWing Insurance in Costa Rica"
  subheadline="The digital nomad favorite. Affordable coverage for tourists and short-term visitors—but understand Costa Rica's unique CAJA requirements."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/costa-rica-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get a SafetyWing Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/safetywing"
>
  <h2 id="overview">SafetyWing in Costa Rica</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing is popular with digital nomads, and Costa Rica is a favorite destination—especially the beach towns and mountain areas. But Costa Rica has unique requirements: legal residents MUST enroll in CAJA (public insurance), and the Rentista visa requires proof of comprehensive coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    SafetyWing Nomad Insurance works for tourists and short-term visitors. For residency applicants or long-term stays, you need to understand Costa Rica's specific requirements.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">$45</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Per 4 weeks (Nomad, age 30)</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">180+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Countries covered</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">0</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Commitment required</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-considerations">Visa Considerations</h2>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Understanding Costa Rica's Requirements</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Costa Rica's residency and insurance rules are different from most countries. <strong>SafetyWing Nomad Insurance may not meet Rentista visa requirements</strong> (which require comprehensive health insurance). For residency applicants, consider a more comprehensive plan for the visa application.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Tourist Visa (90 days)</h3>
  <p>
    No insurance requirement. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance works well for tourists exploring Costa Rica.
  </p>

  <h3>Rentista Visa Application</h3>
  <p>
    Requires proof of private health insurance. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health insurance—it may not be accepted. Remote Health or a traditional insurer is safer for visa applications.
  </p>

  <h3>Pensionado Visa Application</h3>
  <p>
    Requires proof of pension income. Insurance not strictly required for application, but recommended. CAJA enrollment required after approval.
  </p>

  <h3>After Residency Approval</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>CAJA enrollment is mandatory.</strong> All legal residents must pay into Costa Rica's public healthcare system—you cannot opt out. SafetyWing would only supplement CAJA, not replace it.
  </p>

  <h2 id="coverage-types">Coverage Options</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing offers two very different products:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Nomad Insurance (Travel Medical)</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing's famous product—subscription-based travel medical insurance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Emergency medical treatment</li>
    <li>Acute illness that arises while traveling</li>
    <li>Accidents and injuries</li>
    <li>Emergency dental (pain relief only, up to $1,000)</li>
    <li>Medical evacuation up to $100,000</li>
    <li>Lost baggage, travel delays</li>
    <li>Limited US coverage (15 days per 90-day period)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What Nomad Insurance Doesn't Cover</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Routine doctor visits</li>
    <li>Ongoing prescriptions</li>
    <li>Pre-existing conditions</li>
    <li>Mental health</li>
    <li>Maternity</li>
    <li>Dental (except emergency)</li>
    <li>Preventive care</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Remote Health (Full Health Insurance)</h3>
  <p>
    Comprehensive health insurance—completely different from Nomad Insurance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage up to $10 million</li>
    <li>Full outpatient care</li>
    <li>Mental health included</li>
    <li>Maternity available (12-month wait)</li>
    <li>Pre-existing conditions (24-month wait)</li>
    <li>More likely to meet visa requirements</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Understand What You're Buying"
    description="Nomad Insurance is travel medical, not comprehensive health insurance."
    buttonText="Learn More"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    SafetyWing's pricing is simple and transparent:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Nomad Insurance Pricing</h3>
  <p>
    Billed every 4 weeks with no commitment:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Age-based pricing only</li>
    <li>$250 deductible per incident</li>
    <li>One child under 10 free per adult</li>
    <li>Cancel anytime—no penalties</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Remote Health Pricing</h3>
  <p>
    Monthly billing with more variables:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Age affects pricing significantly</li>
    <li>Deductible options: $0-$5,000</li>
    <li>Coverage area affects price</li>
    <li>Higher premiums but comprehensive coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="using-in-costa-rica">Using SafetyWing in Costa Rica</h2>

  <h3>Finding Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing doesn't have a provider network. Use any licensed provider:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Private hospitals (CIMA, Clínica Bíblica)</li>
    <li>Private clinics</li>
    <li>English-speaking doctors (common in San José, expat areas)</li>
    <li>Urgent care centers</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Claims Process</h3>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2">
    <li>Pay the Costa Rican provider upfront</li>
    <li>Get itemized receipt</li>
    <li>Submit claim via SafetyWing portal</li>
    <li>Wait 10-30 days for reimbursement</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Costa Rican Healthcare Costs</h3>
  <p>
    Private healthcare is affordable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Doctor visit: $50-80</li>
    <li>Specialist: $75-150</li>
    <li>Lab work: $30-60</li>
    <li>Urgent care: $80-150</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    You can pay for routine care out of pocket and use SafetyWing for emergencies—if you're a tourist or short-term visitor.
  </p>

  <h2 id="caja-relationship">CAJA and SafetyWing</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding how CAJA affects your insurance options:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">For Residents: CAJA is Mandatory</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800">
      All legal residents MUST enroll in CAJA. You cannot opt out. If you become a Costa Rica resident, SafetyWing (or any private insurance) only supplements CAJA—it doesn't replace it. You'll pay both CAJA (~$75-275/mo) and any private insurance.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>If You're a Tourist</h3>
  <p>
    No CAJA obligation. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance provides emergency coverage. Pay routine care out of pocket (it's affordable).
  </p>

  <h3>If You're Applying for Residency</h3>
  <p>
    You need insurance during the 12-18 month processing period. SafetyWing Remote Health may work; Nomad Insurance likely won't meet Rentista requirements. Consider a comprehensive insurer for the visa application.
  </p>

  <h3>If You're Already a Resident</h3>
  <p>
    CAJA is required. SafetyWing could supplement for travel or private hospital access. But most residents find CAJA + a comprehensive private plan more practical.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose SafetyWing</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Nomad Insurance Good For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>Tourists (90-day stays)</li>
        <li>Digital nomads passing through</li>
        <li>Young, healthy visitors</li>
        <li>Short-term stays without visa needs</li>
        <li>Budget-conscious travelers</li>
        <li>Those testing Costa Rica before committing</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Remote Health May Work For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
        <li>Longer-term stays</li>
        <li>Those wanting comprehensive coverage</li>
        <li>Rentista visa applicants (verify first)</li>
        <li>People with mental health needs</li>
        <li>Pre-residency coverage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Consider Alternatives If:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Applying for Rentista visa</strong> — Need comprehensive insurance</li>
    <li><strong>You're a legal resident</strong> — Must have CAJA anyway; consider fuller supplement</li>
    <li><strong>You have pre-existing conditions</strong> — Nomad Insurance excludes them</li>
    <li><strong>You're over 50</strong> — Consider more comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>You need US coverage</strong> — Aetna or GeoBlue better value</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Right Choice for You?"
    description="Make sure you understand Costa Rica's unique requirements."
    buttonText="Compare All Options"
    buttonHref="/countries/costa-rica/insurance"
  />

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can I use SafetyWing for Costa Rica residency?</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Nomad Insurance likely won't work</strong> for Rentista visa applications which require comprehensive health insurance. Remote Health may be accepted—verify with Costa Rican immigration before applying.
  </p>

  <h3>Do residents need SafetyWing if they have CAJA?</h3>
  <p>
    CAJA is mandatory for all residents. Private insurance supplements CAJA for faster care and private hospitals. SafetyWing could work as a supplement, but most residents prefer a comprehensive private plan alongside CAJA.
  </p>

  <h3>Is SafetyWing enough for tourists in Costa Rica?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. For 90-day tourist stays, Nomad Insurance provides emergency coverage. Costa Rican private healthcare is affordable—pay routine care out of pocket and use SafetyWing for emergencies.
  </p>

  <h3>What about the 12-18 month residency wait?</h3>
  <p>
    You can't access CAJA during residency processing. You need private insurance for this entire period. Remote Health may work; consider a comprehensive insurer if you need coverage that definitely meets visa requirements.
  </p>

  <h3>Does SafetyWing cover private hospitals in Costa Rica?</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing covers any licensed provider. You'll pay upfront and claim reimbursement—there's no direct billing arrangement with CIMA, Clínica Bíblica, or other Costa Rican hospitals.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Understand Your Options"
    description="Choose insurance that fits Costa Rica's unique requirements."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. SafetyWing Nomad Insurance is travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health insurance. Costa Rica requires CAJA enrollment for all legal residents. Verify visa requirements with Costa Rican immigration before relying on any insurance for residency applications.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
